      "originalText": "Your code implements **Insertion Sort**, which builds the sorted array **one element at a time**.\n\nLet's understand it line by line.\n\n---\n\n## Step 1: Initial Array\n\n```java\nint arr[] = {5, 4, 1, 3, 2};\n```\n\n```\nIndex : 0 1 2 3 4\nArray : 5 4 1 3 2\n```\n\nThe first element (`5`) is considered **already sorted**.\n\n```\nSorted | Unsorted\n[5]    | [4 1 3 2]\n```\n\n---\n\n# Step 2: Outer Loop\n\n```java\nfor(int i = 1; i < arr.length; i++)\n```\n\nStarts from index **1** because index **0** is already considered sorted.\n\nEach iteration inserts one element into its correct position in the sorted part.\n\n---\n\n# First Iteration (i = 1)\n\n```java\ncurr = arr[1];\n```\n\n```\ncurr = 4\n```\n\n```java\nprev = i - 1;\n```\n\n```\nprev = 0\n```\n\nCurrent array\n\n```\n5 4 1 3 2\n^ ^\nP C\n```\n\n---\n\n## While Loop\n\n```java\nwhile(prev >= 0 && arr[prev] > curr)\n```\n\nChecks:\n\n```\narr[0] = 5\n\n5 > 4 ✔\n```\n\nShift element right\n\n```java\narr[prev + 1] = arr[prev];\n```\n\n```\n5 5 1 3 2\n```\n\nMove prev left\n\n```java\nprev--;\n```\n\n```\nprev = -1\n```\n\nLoop stops.\n\nInsert current element\n\n```java\narr[prev + 1] = curr;\n```\n\n```\narr[0] = 4\n```\n\nArray becomes\n\n```\n4 5 1 3 2\n```\n\nSorted part\n\n```\n[4 5] [1 3 2]\n```\n\n---\n\n# Second Iteration (i = 2)\n\n```\ncurr = 1\nprev = 1\n```\n\nArray\n\n```\n4 5 1 3 2\n```\n\nCompare\n\n```\n5 > 1 ✔\n```\n\nShift\n\n```\n4 5 5 3 2\n```\n\n```\nprev = 0\n```\n\nAgain\n\n```\n4 > 1 ✔\n```\n\nShift\n\n```\n4 4 5 3 2\n```\n\n```\nprev = -1\n```\n\nInsert\n\n```\narr[0] = 1\n```\n\nArray\n\n```\n1 4 5 3 2\n```\n\nSorted part\n\n```\n[1 4 5] [3 2]\n```\n\n---\n\n# Third Iteration (i = 3)\n\n```\ncurr = 3\nprev = 2\n```\n\nArray\n\n```\n1 4 5 3 2\n```\n\nCompare\n\n```\n5 > 3 ✔\n```\n\nShift\n\n```\n1 4 5 5 2\n```\n\n```\nprev = 1\n```\n\nCompare\n\n```\n4 > 3 ✔\n```\n\nShift\n\n```\n1 4 4 5 2\n```\n\n```\nprev = 0\n```\n\nCompare\n\n```\n1 > 3 ✖\n```\n\nStop.\n\nInsert\n\n```\narr[1] = 3\n```\n\nArray\n\n```\n1 3 4 5 2\n```\n\n---\n\n# Fourth Iteration (i = 4)\n\n```\ncurr = 2\nprev = 3\n```\n\nArray\n\n```\n1 3 4 5 2\n```\n\nShift 5\n\n```\n1 3 4 5 5\n```\n\nShift 4\n\n```\n1 3 4 4 5\n```\n\nShift 3\n\n```\n1 3 3 4 5\n```\n\nNow\n\n```\n1 > 2 ✖\n```\n\nInsert\n\n```\narr[1] = 2\n```\n\nFinal array\n\n```\n1 2 3 4 5\n```\n\n---\n\n# Understanding the While Loop\n\n```java\nwhile(prev >= 0 && arr[prev] > curr)\n```\n\nIt means:\n\n* Keep moving left.\n* As long as the previous element is larger than the current element:\n\n  * Shift the larger element one position to the right.\n* Stop when:\n\n  * You reach the beginning of the array, or\n  * You find an element smaller than or equal to `curr`.\n\n---\n\n# Why do we shift instead of swapping?\n\nInsertion Sort **does not swap repeatedly**.\n\nIt:\n\n1. Stores the current element.\n2. Shifts all larger elements one position to the right.\n3. Inserts the stored element into the empty position.\n\nExample:\n\nInstead of\n\n```\n5 4 1\n```\n\ndoing multiple swaps,\n\nit shifts:\n\n```\n5 5 1\n4 5 5\n1 4 5\n```\n\nThis reduces unnecessary swaps.\n\n---\n\n# Dry Run Table\n\n| Iteration | Current (`curr`) | Array After Insertion |\n| --------- | ---------------- | --------------------- |\n| i = 1     | 4                | 4 5 1 3 2             |\n| i = 2     | 1                | 1 4 5 3 2             |\n| i = 3     | 3                | 1 3 4 5 2             |\n| i = 4     | 2                | 1 2 3 4 5             |\n\n---\n\n# Time Complexity\n\n* **Best Case (already sorted):** `O(n)` (the `while` loop doesn't shift anything)\n* **Average Case:** `O(n²)`\n* **Worst Case (reverse sorted):** `O(n²)` (every element shifts through the sorted part)\n\n---\n\n# Easy Exam Definition\n\n**Insertion Sort** is a sorting algorithm that picks one element at a time from the unsorted part and inserts it into its correct position in the sorted part by shifting larger elements to the right.\n\n**Memory trick:** Think of arranging playing cards in your hand—you pick one card and insert it into the correct position among the cards you've already sorted.\n",
